text.tspan: PAGE 1
Girl Scouts Digital Media Course
November 19, 2010 | Session 6
YOUR FIRST ALBUM COVER!
- Become comfortable working with Inkscape layers
goals for the day:
• Learn how to format document areas in Inkscape
• Learn how to Export artwork from Inkscape
QUESTION OF THE DAY:
If you could do an album with any musician today, who would it be? What would
your album title be, and what type of music would you create?
SETTING UP YOUR CANVAS
We're going to create a CD album cover for
your musical collaboration! First we need to
set up a canvas in Inkscape so when your
album cover is printed, it will fit inside a CD
case. CD album covers are 4.75" x 4.75".
• Learn how to import Gimp artwork into Inkscape
(ORIGINAL PHOTO)
BLEND A PHOTO WITH
ANOTHER PHOTO!
BLEND A PHOTO WITH
ITSELF!
BLEND A PHOTO WITH
A FILL OR PATTERN!
(screening Nicki to make her brighter)
Next, select a layer blending mode for the photo on top. Experiment.
Depending on the photos you've chosen, you may want to flip or move the
photos to strengthen your composition.
Try changing the order of the photos. Depending on which photo is on the top
and which photo is o the bottom, the final effect may look different. You may
do these by selecting a layer to move (simply
click on it), then click either the layer up button
or the layer down button.
LAYER UP
BUTTON
LAYER DOWN
BUTTON
Feel free to blend as many photos together as
you'd like. You can stick with to or work with
10. It's up to you. You can also use fill or pattern
layers inbetween as well.
REVIEW QUESTIONS
Can you name three layer blending modes? How does each make your image
look when you use it?
For really cool face-paint effects, try to
find a photo of an animal or pattern to face
paint onto your face. For example, find a photo
of fish scales or a zebra's fur. Then, use a layer
mask to 'paint' the animal's pattern onto your
face.
How do you create a gradient?
How would you dye your hair pink using the Gimp, step-by-step?
What tool would you use to make a layer transparet?
EXTRA CREDIT
Find a photo of your favorite celebrity, and turn them into a zombie for Halloween!

Different fonts can give your logo a different feel and impression. How do each
of the fonts above come across to you?
You can install even more fonts on your USB.
Visit fontsquirrel.com, download their zip
files & double-click on the zip files. Double-
click on the TTF or OTF files, and you'll see
a preview of the font and an install button.
Click on the button, restart Inkscape, and
the font should appear in the font list!
MgOpen Moderna
INSTALLING MORE FONTS!
Open up Inkscape, and select the File > New
> Default menu item. Then go to File >
Document Properties. Select "In" for inches
under Units, and put "4.75" for both the
Width and Height in the window. Then
exit the window with the 'X' in the upper-
right corner.
(This screenshot shows where you
have to fill in these values!)
IMPORTING IMAGES
You should now have a CD album cover sized square in your Inkscape window!
You may want to find photographs or use some of your previous class work on your
album cover design. You may also want to create a new image, work on it in the
Gimp, and then bring it into Inkscape. Do you remember where to find photos?
http://creativecommons.org/search
You can import images that are in SVG, PNG, JPG, or GIF format into Inkscape. You
can tell which an image is by its name. What type of image is the example below?
nicki-minaj.jpg
This is a JPG - it ends with .jpg.
